# Phrasal Verbs - English Grammar

<big><b>PHRASAL VERBS</b></big>

A <b>phrasal verb</b> is a combination of:

• A verb
• One or two particles (preposition or adverb)

The meaning is often different from the original verb.

Examples:
• Wake up
• Turn on
• Give up
• Look for

---

<big><b>Common Phrasal Verbs</b></big>

1. Wake up
   Meaning: stop sleeping
   Example:
   • I wake up at 6 AM.

2. Turn on
   Meaning: activate something
   Example:
   • Turn on the computer.

3. Turn off
   Meaning: deactivate something
   Example:
   • Please turn off the lights.

4. Give up
   Meaning: stop trying
   Example:
   • Never give up.

5. Look for
   Meaning: search
   Example:
   • I am looking for my keys.

6. Pick up
   Meaning: collect or lift
   Example:
   • She picked up the book.

7. Sit down
   Meaning: take a seat
   Example:
   • Please sit down.

8. Get up
   Meaning: leave the bed
   Example:
   • He gets up early.

---

<big><b>Separable Phrasal Verbs</b></big>

Some phrasal verbs can be separated.

Example:
• Turn on the TV.
• Turn the TV on.

Both are correct.

---

<big><b>Inseparable Phrasal Verbs</b></big>

Some phrasal verbs cannot be separated.

Example:
• I am looking for my phone.

Incorrect:
• I am looking my phone for.

---

<big><b>Phrasal Verbs with Pronouns</b></big>

When using pronouns, the pronoun usually goes in the middle.

Examples:
• Turn it off.
• Pick it up.
• Put them away.

---

<big><b>Daily Life Phrasal Verbs</b></big>

• Go out
• Come in
• Wake up
• Sit down
• Stand up
• Put on
• Take off

Examples:
• She put on her jacket.
• They went out last night.
• Take off your shoes.

---

<big><b>Practice Exercises</b></big>

Complete the sentences:

1. Please turn ____ the TV.
2. I am looking ____ my backpack.
3. He gave ____ smoking.
4. She woke ____ late.
5. Pick ____ the paper.

Answers:

1. off
2. for
3. up
4. up
5. up

